{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_etna_ver03/data/sn83002748/00514150205/1920092301/0984.xml":{"full_text":"NATION MAKES GREAT STRIPES.\nSurvey of United States by Franklin\nK. Lane Shows Progress in\nMany Branches.\nFranklin K. Lane, former Secretary\nof the Interior, on Tuesday issued a\nstatement making public a summary of\nwhat he calls \u2022\u2018The first comprehensive.;\ncarefully made and approximately ac\ncurate picture of industrial, agricul\ntural. financial and jxilitical conditions\nthroughout the United States.\u201d It dis\ncovers in the foreground, he says, that\nboth major political parties have over\nlooked the greatest issue in the public\nmind, which is the cost of living. It\nalso shows, he states, that the country\nis on a sound economic basis, with the\nwave of extravagance subsiding, sav\ning increasing, wholesalers and retail\ners optimistic over the winter out\nlook. and a growing disj>osition for hard\nwork, although the individual produc\ntivity of labor is not yet showing much\nevidence of increase.\nMr. Lane\u2019s statement sumniarizvs a\nsurvey made through POO field repre\nsentatives of the Fidelity and Deposit\nCompany of Maryland and covers every\nsection of the country. Manufacturers,\nmerchants, (\u2019handlers of Commerce,\nbankers, lawyers, businessmen and far\nmers were questioned in the effort to\nmirror the immediate economic and po\nlitical situation and obtain a concensus\n<>f representative opinion as to the fu\nture. The replies from all localities\nwere made simultaneously by telegraph.\nIn a preface to his analysis of the\nsurvey. Mr. Lane says: \u201cWith the\npresidential election but six weeks\naway and the winter rapidly approach\ning. many thoughtful people stand\nhesitant and undecided, having diffi\nculty because of the general lack of\nknowledge of business conditions out\nside their own locality or interests.\nThe general tendency has lieen to see\nwhat the next man thinks, with the\nuncomfortable feeling that bis guess\nis no better than another\u2019s. I believe,\nfor this reason, the picture presented\nin the tabulated analysis is of great\ninterest to every business man and I\nvoter. While it is not, of course, per\nfect in detail and exact in prophecy it\nis as clear and valuable a conspectus\nof present conditions us can lie gath\nered.\u201d\nUnder the heading of industrial con-{\n\u2022lit ions. Mr. Lam* says: \u201cEconomical-|\nly. the United States is shown to Im* j\nbetter off than any other country in\nthe world. There is no evidence of\nIdleness. Our fieople have the oppor-I\n(unity to work and are nt work.\n\u2018\u2022There is no shortage of raw ma- 1\n(\u2666\u2022rials sufficient to curtail production, i\nreported from any of the nine geo-\ngraphical districts into which the\ncountry was divided for the purpose of\nthe survey. Only in the district in\ncluding Minnesota, the Dakotas. lowa.\nKansas. Nebraska and Wisconsin, is\nthere evidence of lack of orders. New\nEngland industries report a number of\n\u00ab*an<*el hit ions, but there, as elsewhere,\nmanufacturers are well filled with calls\nfor their product.\n'\u201cTransportation conditions are im\nproving everywlwn* and a substantial\nreduction in ll.r freight car shortage is\nreported in every district except in the\nR<M*ky Mountain Stales, in the South\nwest and in the district including Ken\ntucky. Tennessee. Alabama and Missis\nsippi. although an improvement is not\ned in the latter district.\n\u201cA shortage of coal and the failure\nof lulxir to increase individual pnaluc\ntivity appear to Im* the only two un\nfavorable aspects in the imm<*diate in\ndustrial situation. The Rocky Moun\ntain and Pacific States report a suffi\ncient supply of fuel. All other sec\ntions of the country are feeling the\nshortage but it is ap]mrently least felt\nby the South Atlantic states.\n\"Although labor is costing still more\nthan it did last year, it apparently is j\nproducing no more. Wages have ad\nvanced from 10 to 50 per cent, in the\nlast twelve months and yet nowhere is i\n(here reported increase in productivity\nI Small Ranches 1\nI have a few Small Ranches,\n.1 160 and 320 acres, that can\nbe purchased very cheap and\non easy terms. Inquire\nM.B.McKillip\n1 Real Estate Insurance. Saratoga, Wyoming.\n\nper man. I am not expecting that the\ncost of labor will fall off even in the\nworst of times to its pre-war stage, for\nI lielleve that the real differential Im*-\ntween directing labor and manual la-\nI bor will never again Im* as great as it\ni has been.\nI \u201cSo far as the distiibntion of labor\nis concerned, the situation nationally\nappears to Im* well equalized. A short\nage of labor is found only in the Middle\nAtlantic and South Atlantic states and\nthis is largely of unskilled workers.\nIn the rest of the country the demand\ninml supply appear balanced* Only\ni in some sections of tin* Middle Atlantic\nstates is any unemployment reported\nami this is in certain of the skilled\n\ntrades, chiefly the building and ship\nbuilding trades.\nI \u201cAn im]M>rtant disclosure of the sur-\nI vey is the seriousness of the housing\nsituation. In many of the large indus\ntrial centers where the shortage has\nbeen most acute the investigation has\ndisclosed building oiM*rations to be de-\ncreasing instead of increasing.\nI \u201cThe call for buildings comes loud-\nI est from the most essential places of\nmanufacture rather than from the re\ntail centers and is for low priced dwell\nings. Building construction is increas\ning in New England, but the bulk of the\nconstruction is of factories, warehouses\nand stores. New York. Pennsylvania\nami most of the other great industrial\n\u2018\u2022states of the East ami Middle West\nshow a falling off in building opera\ntions. Then* is improvement in the\nPacific Coast industrial centers with\n\u2019{special emphasis on the erection of\nworkmen\u2019s homes.\ni \u201cIn no section of the country did the\ninvestigators find sentiment in favor\n\u2019.of government ownership of the rail\nroads: and everywhere* better transpor\ntation conditions are reported.\n\u201cAgriculture generally is recognized\njas the backlMine of the country, and\nthe farming situation is excellent\nfrom no section has an unfavorable re\nport been received. Our farmers ap\npear everywhere to be in too happy a\niikmml to permit the cynicism. \u2018The far\nmer is always grumbling.\u2019 They are\nwell supplied with funds from the sale\n'of this year\u2019s crop, but they are wise\nin that they know that more favorable\nmarketing conditions can Im* created.\n\"The recent drop in grain prices is\nreported to have had no effect except\nin the Rocky Mountain states. Fann\n:ers of Illinois. Indiana. Michigan, Wis\ni cousin and other Central states are\nj withholding grain.\n\u201cIn tin* financial field, money is tight.\nThat may mean several things; First,\nthat the people want money badly to\nput into producing activities; second,\nthat tin* banks attempt to get what\never the traffic will lM*ar. shearing close\nI to the skin third, that there is an ade\n'quate supply of money, or fourth, that\nthose who have money lack confi\ndeuce. There are other reasons, no\nI doubt, and among them that the dollar\nnow buys less than heretofore, people\nwith money wish to charge more for\nthe service than money gives. No one\ncan accurately say which of these\ncauses is the most important factor,\nbut probably all contribute to the\npresent situation.\n\"The telegraphic rei>orts from every\nsection of the country state that the\nbanks are well loaned up. although\nmoney is available in the East and Cen\ntral districts at from six to eight per\ncent interest. Tin* Southwest, Rocky\nMountain and Pacific slates report the\nhighest interest rales, averaging from\n8 to 10 jn*r cent., and in the mountain\ndistrict as high as 12 per cent.\n\u201cThen* is great encouragement how\never to Im* drawn from the fact that in\nonly one of the nine geographical divi\nsions, the Rocky Mountain, has there\nlieen a decrease in bank deposits dur\ning the last six months. While the\ngeneral increase includes corporation\ndeposits. Individual savings accounts\nI show more marked improvement every\nwhen*. This seems to show clearly\nthat the orgy of spending ami extra v\ni agance is over.\nj \u201cDiscounting of bills by industrial\nI concerns is universally reported. Ex-i\n_\n01920\nLook at the\nroads for twenty miles\naround on a Sundaq\nTHERE isn\u2019t any \"country They make no distinction\nany more. The automo- between the small car\nbile has brought the most owner and the owner of the\nremote settlement almost as biggest car in the country.\nclose to the center of things It>s aU the same to them\nas the next county was in So long as a man owns an\nthe old days. automobile large or small\nH \u2014he\u2019s entitled to the very\nTo hear some tire dealers best tire they can give him.\ntalk you might think that Quality has alwayc? becn\nnobody knew anything about the outstanding feature oi\ntires exoe P t the fcllow from U. S. Tires. There\u2019s no\nIn sandy or hilly coun- Broadway\ntry. wherever the going limit on the U. S. guarantee,\nis apt to be heavy\u2014The\nu s No^ by That\u2019s not the basis we All U. S. Tires are guaranteed\nFor ordinary country\nThe u s Ch go on. for the life of the tire.\nFor front wheels\u2014The\nresult,- Wc g ivC eVer y Cfedit V\nRoyafcOTd\u2122 V S for knowing what he is We have given a lot of\nspending his money on, thought to this tire proposi\nwhether he drives up here tion. There is some advan\nin his small car from ten tage in being the represent\nmiles out in the country or ativesof the oldestandlargest\nis passing through from the rubber concern in the world,\ncapital in his limousine. Drop in the next time\n111 you\u2019re down this way and\nThat\u2019s one thing wc like let us tell you some interest\nabout U. S. Tires. ing facts about tires.\nUnited States Tires\nI\nFOR SALE BY\nWyoming Garage, Saratoga, Wyo. National Garage, Encampment. Wyoming.\n<i p! in the Middle Atlantic, South\nI western and Pacific Coast states, man\nufacturers appear to la? carrying large\namounts of customers paper.\n\u201cThe country does not like the pres-\nent taxation system. The excess pro\nfits tax is in bad favor everywhere.\nipinion is divided, however, as to a\nsubstitute. In the East and Central\nWest sentiment runs strongly for a\nsales tax. but elsewhere opinion as to\na substitute is divided.\n\u201cWe ar<\u00bb not yet masters of tlie art\nof distribution of product. The fact\nthat the farmers uniformly report a\ndesire for some co-operative method by\nwhich their products can lie brought\nto consumers moans that this problem\nis of the greatest importance. But it\nis not for the farmers benefit primarily\nthat such a movement must quickly\nculminate in action.\n\u201cThe consumer feels that somewhere\nIx\u00bb tween the farmer and himself too\nmuch is taken for a service of compar- J\native insignificance in contrast with\nthat whit\u2019ll the producer himself ren\nders.\n\u201cTlie farmers apparently are not I\nalone in desiring co-operative action.\nThe survey shows opposition to co\noperative movements only in the new\nEngland and Pacific Coast district*.\nSentiment is divided in Ohio. Illinois\nand the other North Central and Went- j\nern states, but favorable in tlie Middle\nAtlantic, the South Central and the*\nTHE SABATOGA SCN\n_ f\n1 Southern states.\n\u201cPolitically the replies indicate that\nit is to early to tell what the outcome j\nlof the Novemlier election will be. Three 1\ni months ago there was a stronger Repub\nllican sentiment than there appears to\nla* now. The trend has been, and Is,\nRepublican. What it will lx* in Nov\nember these gentlemen do not prophesy.\n\u201cThe large outstanding fact dvvel-'\noped seems to Is* that the greatest is\nsue in tlie public mind is being over\nlooked by the campaigner*\u2014the high\ncost of living. 1 think this conclusion\nwill Im* justified but the blame should 1\nnot Im* cast upon the producer and cer- j\nt a inly the farmer has not received his\nshare of the wealth -which he creates. I\n\u201cThe cost of living ami foreign rela\ntions seem to lx* the main issues. Tax\nation and industrial relations also oc- 4\ncupy a space in the general political 1\nthought. Ix*ast interest appears to be\nI shown in tlie railroad policy of the j\npresent administration, radical move-\nmeats mid prohibition.\n\u201cIt is clear that the country is on a\nsound economic basis and there is gen\ni <*rally a spirit of confidence in the\nfuture, regardless of tlie outcome of!\ntlie election.\n\u201cThe business outlook appears to be i\ngood in every section. Wholesalers\nand retailers view the fall and winter\noptimistically. The retailer is finding j\nthat the consumer is looking forward\nI without fear to tin* winter, and his!\npurchases from the wholesaler are\nI\n4-4-4-4-4\u20184*4*4*4\u00ab4-4-4-4 4*4\u20194 4-4\u20194 4\u20194\u00ab4\u20194*4\u00ab4\u00bb4\u2018\u00abF4\u00bb4\u00ab4\u00ab4\u00bb4\u00bb\n4* 4*\nLight and Heavy Dray\nQuick Transportation 4-\n4I Reliable Deliveries j\n4. Anything Transported J\n\u2019t* Local Agent Continental Oil Company 4*\nEverett A. Gross, Prop, i\ni\nfounded upon this optimism. From the\nsimple toiler up through tu the trades- 1\ni man. to the industry and the financier,\n\u2019there runs the connected feeling of\nconfidence.\u201d\n\nWyoming a Good Wlieat Producer. 1 1\nAccording to the monthly bulletin of\n.the Federal Reserve District, Wyoming\nis up with tlie top-notchers hi the pro\nduction of wheat per acre in recent!\nyears, and has it over all other states\nof the district hi the yield jx*r acre in a\nten-year average. According to the\nbulletin. Wyoming and (\u2019oloiado head.\nI the list for acre yield the past year\nI with an average of 20 buxiu is, Miss- i\nouri having the low average with 12%\nbushels. Kansas, Nebraska, New M^xi-*\nico and Oklahoma are the other states\nIncluded in this district. In the ten\nyear average Wyoming is given 23.1\nbushel* per acre, the next highest Im--\nhig Colorado, with 20.2 biwhele, and\nthe lowest Im-lii\u00df Oklahoma with 12.0\nbushels per ncre.\nSlliiH Igo, brother of E. B. Igo of\nSaratoga. arrived hist night with sev\neral other men from Indianola. lowa,\n!to look over ranch lands In this sec\n(lon.\nAlbert Nixon Is having material\nhauhsl for the construction of four new\nconcrete crossings, the contract for\nWhich was recently awarded him by\nthe city.\nHave you read the want ads?","height":"21216","width":"15656"}}
